7,'_side_panel','field_59131ac61186e'),(2416,458,'hero_image','Aya-hero-2.png'),(2417,458,'_hero_image','field_57d2bacfc7bdd'),(2418,458,'sub_text','Aya has been created out of a need to live and work authentically with a vision of creating a business for good'),(2419,458,'_sub_text','field_57e90fea19072'),(2420,458,'side_panel',''),(2421,458,'_side_panel','field_59131ac61186e'),(2422,459,'hero_image','Aya-butterDishes-3.png'),(2423,459,'_hero_image','field_57d2bacfc7bdd'),(2424,459,'sub_text','No one can do it alone and no one can take all of the credit'),(2425,459,'_sub_text','field_57e90fea19072'),(2426,459,'side_panel',''),(2427,459,'_side_panel','field_59131ac61186e'),(2428,460,'hero_image','Aya-butterDishes-3.png'),(2429,460,'_hero_image','field_57d2bacfc7bdd'),(2430,460,'sub_text','No one can do it alone and no one can take all of the credit'),(2431,460,'_sub_text','field_57e90fea19072'),(2432,460,'side_panel',''),(2433,460,'_side_panel','field_59131ac61186e'),(2434,461,'hero_image','Aya-butterDish-1.png'),(2435,461,'_hero_image','field_57d2bacfc7bdd'),(2436,461,'sub_text','Plantbased alternatives kinder to you, the earth and the animals'),(2437,461,'_sub_text','field_57e90fea19072'),(2438,461,'side_panel',''),(2439,461,'_side_panel','field_59131ac61186e'),(2440,462,'hero_image','Aya-butterDish-1.png'),(2441,462,'_hero_image','field_57d2bacfc7bdd'),(2442,462,'sub_text','Plantbased alternatives kinder to you, the earth and the animals'),(2443,462,'_sub_text','field_57e90fea19072'),(2444,462,'side_panel',''),(2445,462,'_side_panel','field_59131ac61186e'),(2446,463,'_edit_last','1'),(2447,463,'_edit_lock','1512186113:1'),(2449,464,'hero_image',''),(2450,464,'_hero_image','field_57d2bacfc7bdd'),(2451,464,'intro','We can create a new culture where individuals are inspired to try without fear and stigma of failure'),(2452,464,'_intro','field_57ebd1b41c03b'),(2453,464,'sub_text','<p class=\"western\">I recently attended a competitive 2 day event based around creating an investable business opportunity that met UN\'s SDG12 (sustainable development goal) - responsible consumption and production. This was an opportunity for me to learn more about business, sustainability in business and to interact with like minded people.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">Once the event kicked off I spontaneously decided to pitch my potential business, Aya. With this mind-set I immediately became an active participant. I found myself trying to recruit participants to join my team, intently encouraging ideas and interest.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">The pitch phase arrived. Everyone was given 3 elastic bands. Once all 10 of us had presented our 30 second pitch participants were given an opportunity to give away their elastic bands to the pitches they were most interested in. </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">Presenting the pitch was obviously quite stressful, as everyone knows public speaking isn\'t easy especially when you haven\'t had a lot of practice. What was even more stressful was standing around waiting for participants to hand over their elastic bands. I got two elastic bands, an abysmal performance considering their were approximately 150 elastic bands available. Suffice to say my pitch didn\'t make the final 7.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">Once we had all formed teams around the winning 7 pitches we started the hard work of creating an investable business opportunity that met SDG12. The following morning we returned knowing that our presentations needed to be completed by lunch time. It was a test of team work, collaboration, compromise, clear communication and good business acumen. Finally we were all ready to pitch to our investors. Each pitch was 4 minutes followed by a short Q &amp; A with the judges. Once all the pitches had been presented the judges deliberated and returned with a winner and a runner-up. Unfortunately our team was unsuccessful.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">I found the whole event very stressful. My decision to be an active participant meant that from the start I had made myself vulnerable to success or failure. When I was forced to face the rejection of my first pitch it was a very difficult time. I wasn\'t able to stay present, to be in the moment. I found myself creating illusions about how the other participants perceived me, slipping back into old stories of victimhood. It took me a while to find my strength and inner worth. I kept breathing pulling myself back to the here and now and thankfully I did recover and focused on helping my team.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">On the tube home at the end of the event I started to think about the difference between success and failure? Logically success or failure is based on accurately achieving a goal, an aim or a purpose. In competitive scenarios the successor is the one who comes closest to achieving a goal, aim or purpose. With this in mind the first thing we need to do to be successful is clearly understand the goal, aim or purpose. I realised that I had paid no attention to the point system that has been assigned to the pitches. How will I ever be successful if I don\'t keep the goal clearly in mind?</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">But perhaps the biggest difference between success and failure is our response to it. I imagined how my team would have responded if we had been successful. We would have glowed with pride and smiled with accomplishment. We would have praised each other on our efforts, quickly forgetting the difficulties that we had faced. We would have been open to integrating with other participants, taking praise and talking about how and what we had done to achieve our success.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">And how did we act in failure? We were outwardly sympathetic towards our team members. We were introvert, retrospective, critical and analytical. We wanted to to expose the weeds and acknowledge the areas of weakness. We made comparisons about the validity of our idea compared with those that were successful, keen to discover the key to their success. </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">We all know that failure is inevitable, it is a part of life. Some say that failure is the key to success and perhaps that is true but only in so far as you choose to learn from your failure. If failure has you feeling so hurt and disheartened that you decide not to expose yourself and give up then it won\'t help you succeed. With this in mind we must choose our goal, aim or purpose carefully. If we are passionate about achieving our goal, aim or purpose because we know that it will bring us lasting fulfilment, satisfaction and happiness then we are more likely to learn from our failures allowing them to further motivate us to try again.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">The best thing we can do to alleviate the suffering we create around failure is to respond to it the same as success. We can glow with pride and smile with accomplishment because we gave it a try, because without those that try, those that are willing to expose themselves and make themselves vulnerable humanity will not progress. If we can fail with a smile on our face in the knowledge that we will learn from our mistakes, then we can create a new culture where individuals are inspired to try without fear and stigma of failure. If in failure we can be equally retrospective and analytical about our strengths and our weaknesses then having identified our strengths we can play a better, stronger hand and we can celebrate our strengths despite failure.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">And just as importantly, if in success we can maintain humility, if we reject feelings of superiority, grandiosity and importance and if we respond just as we do in failure then we narrow the gap between success and failure and we highlight the significance and importance of the journey rather than the achievement of a goal, aim or purpose.</span></p>'),(2454,464,'_sub_text','field_57e90fea19072'),(2455,463,'hero_image','success-failure.jpeg'),(2456,463,'_hero_image','field_57d2bacfc7bdd'),(2457,463,'intro','We narrow the gap between success and failure and highlight the significance and importance of the journey rather than the achievement of a goal'),(2458,463,'_intro','field_57ebd1b41c03b'),(2459,463,'sub_text','We can create a new culture where individuals are inspired to try without fear and the stigma of failure'),(2460,463,'_sub_text','field_57e90fea19072'),(2462,465,'hero_image',''),(2463,465,'_hero_image','field_57d2bacfc7bdd'),(2464,465,'intro','if in success we can maintain humility, if we reject feelings of superiority, grandiosity and importance and if we respond just as we do in failure then we narrow the gap between success and failure and we highlight the significance and importance of the journey rather than the achievement of a goal, aim or purpose.'),(2465,465,'_intro','field_57ebd1b41c03b'),(2466,465,'sub_text','<p class=\"western\">I recently attended a competitive 2 day event based around creating an investable business opportunity that met UN\'s SDG12 (sustainable development goal) - responsible consumption and production. This was an opportunity for me to learn more about business, sustainability in business and to interact with like minded people.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">Once the event kicked off I spontaneously decided to pitch my potential business, Aya. With this mind-set I immediately became an active participant. I found myself trying to recruit participants to join my team, intently encouraging ideas and interest.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">The pitch phase arrived. Everyone was given 3 elastic bands. Once all 10 of us had presented our 30 second pitch participants were given an opportunity to give away their elastic bands to the pitches they were most interested in. </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">Presenting the pitch was obviously quite stressful, as everyone knows public speaking isn\'t easy especially when you haven\'t had a lot of practice. What was even more stressful was standing around waiting for participants to hand over their elastic bands. I got two elastic bands, an abysmal performance considering their were approximately 150 elastic bands available. Suffice to say my pitch didn\'t make the final 7.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">Once we had all formed teams around the winning 7 pitches we started the hard work of creating an investable business opportunity that met SDG12. The following morning we returned knowing that our presentations needed to be completed by lunch time. It was a test of team work, collaboration, compromise, clear communication and good business acumen. Finally we were all ready to pitch to our investors. Each pitch was 4 minutes followed by a short Q &amp; A with the judges. Once all the pitches had been presented the judges deliberated and returned with a winner and a runner-up. Unfortunately our team was unsuccessful.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">I found the whole event very stressful. My decision to be an active participant meant that from the start I had made myself vulnerable to success or failure. When I was forced to face the rejection of my first pitch it was a very difficult time. I wasn\'t able to stay present, to be in the moment. I found myself creating illusions about how the other participants perceived me, slipping back into old stories of victimhood. It took me a while to find my strength and inner worth. I kept breathing pulling myself back to the here and now and thankfully I did recover and focused on helping my team.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">On the tube home at the end of the event I started to think about the difference between success and failure? Logically success or failure is based on accurately achieving a goal, an aim or a purpose. In competitive scenarios the successor is the one who comes closest to achieving a goal, aim or purpose. With this in mind the first thing we need to do to be successful is clearly understand the goal, aim or purpose. I realised that I had paid no attention to the point system that has been assigned to the pitches. How will I ever be successful if I don\'t keep the goal clearly in mind?</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">But perhaps the biggest difference between success and failure is our response to it. I imagined how my team would have responded if we had been successful. We would have glowed with pride and smiled with accomplishment. We would have praised each other on our efforts, quickly forgetting the difficulties that we had faced. We would have been open to integrating with other participants, taking praise and talking about how and what we had done to achieve our success.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">And how did we act in failure? We were outwardly sympathetic towards our team members. We were introvert, retrospective, critical and analytical. We wanted to to expose the weeds and acknowledge the areas of weakness. We made comparisons about the validity of our idea compared with those that were successful, keen to discover the key to their success. </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">We all know that failure is inevitable, it is a part of life. Some say that failure is the key to success and perhaps that is true but only in so far as you choose to learn from your failure. If failure has you feeling so hurt and disheartened that you decide not to expose yourself and give up then it won\'t help you succeed. With this in mind we must choose our goal, aim or purpose carefully. If we are passionate about achieving our goal, aim or purpose because we know that it will bring us lasting fulfilment, satisfaction and happiness then we are more likely to learn from our failures allowing them to further motivate us to try again.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">The best thing we can do to alleviate the suffering we create around failure is to respond to it the same as success. We can glow with pride and smile with accomplishment because we gave it a try, because without those that try, those that are willing to expose themselves and make themselves vulnerable humanity will not progress. If we can fail with a smile on our face in the knowledge that we will learn from our mistakes, then we can create a new culture where individuals are inspired to try without fear and stigma of failure. If in failure we can be equally retrospective and analytical about our strengths and our weaknesses then having identified our strengths we can play a better, stronger hand and we can celebrate our strengths despite failure.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">And just as importantly, if in success we can maintain humility, if we reject feelings of superiority, grandiosity and importance and if we respond just as we do in failure then we narrow the gap between success and failure and we highlight the significance and importance of the journey rather than the achievement of a goal, aim or purpose.</span></p>'),(2467,465,'_sub_text','field_57e90fea19072'),(2471,467,'hero_image','Success-and-failure.jpeg'),(2472,467,'_hero_image','field_57d2bacfc7bdd'),(2473,467,'intro','if in success we can maintain humility, if we reject feelings of superiority, grandiosity and importance and if we respond just as we do in failure then we narrow the gap between success and failure and we highlight the significance and importance of the journey rather than the achievement of a goal, aim or purpose.'),(2474,467,'_intro','field_57ebd1b41c03b'),(2475,467,'sub_text','<p class=\"western\">I recently attended a competitive 2 day event based around creating an investable business opportunity that met UN\'s SDG12 (sustainable development goal) - responsible consumption and production. This was an opportunity for me to learn more about business, sustainability in business and to interact with like minded people.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">Once the event kicked off I spontaneously decided to pitch my potential business, Aya. With this mind-set I immediately became an active participant. I found myself trying to recruit participants to join my team, intently encouraging ideas and interest.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">The pitch phase arrived. Everyone was given 3 elastic bands. Once all 10 of us had presented our 30 second pitch participants were given an opportunity to give away their elastic bands to the pitches they were most interested in. </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\">Presenting the pitch was obviously quite stressful, as everyone knows public speaking isn\'t easy especially when you haven\'t had a lot of practice. What was even more stressful was standing around waiting for participants to hand over their elastic bands. I got two elastic bands, an abysmal performance considering their were approximately 150 el