sed','closed','','103-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 13:52:51','2016-10-13 13:52:51','',103,'http://blog.calloftheforest.com/103-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(131,1,'2016-10-14 14:26:31','2016-10-14 14:26:31','<p>I have been consuming a vegan and organic diet for the past two years. I made the decision for ethical reasons due to my concerns with the mistreatment of animals in the meat and dairy industry as well as the strain that animal agriculture and chemicals have on the environment.</p>\r\n<p>Initially this was a relaxed decision, however as the years have gone¬†by I am finding it increasingly difficult to eat meat, dairy or un-organic food.</p>\r\n<p>Eating a vegan diet¬†has an interesting learning curve.¬† One has to meet all¬†their nutritional requirements without meat or dairy sources.¬† It\'s not impossible but it does take some careful choices and a clear understanding of the nutrients we need and in what foods they are found.¬† It also requires listening to your body and noticing when things aren\'t quite right.</p>\r\n<p>I\'ve noticed that I¬†depend on¬†¬†lots of¬†\'exotic\' ingredients that aren\'t sourced locally.¬† Things like hemp seeds, chia seeds and Spirulina.¬† In fact most of my protein sources like chickpeas, kidney beans, quinoa and lentils are not sourced locally.¬† It has me wondering if I am creating a¬†bigger carbon footprint than if I just ate locally sourced ingredients which might include meat and dairy.</p>\r\n<p>The point is that if¬†it were proven that my carbon footprint¬†was larger than if I ate locally sourced foods I would need to reconsider my choices.¬† Which brings me back to the difficulty I have eating meat, dairy or un-organic food.¬† Have I become identified with being vegan?¬† Does it give me satisfaction to say \'I\'m vegan\'?¬† Do I think I am better than others and judge them because they aren\'t vegan?¬† Being identified with veganism is of little benefit as it means that I¬†have become¬†closed to new¬†information and defensive about my¬†opinions.</p>\r\n<p>That\'s why I¬†believe that eating consciously is most important.¬† It\'s not about making judgements or identifications, its about doing what\' right for the greatest good.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><span>In every truth the opposite is equally true.¬†That is to say, any truth can only be expressed and put into words when it is one-sided. Everything that can be thought with the mind and said with words is one-sided, it\'s all just the half of it, lacking completeness, roundness, or unity.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>Siddhartha by Hermann Hesse</p>','Nothing is black or white','','publish','open','open','','nothing-is-black-or-white','','','2017-11-14 16:54:11','2017-11-14 16:54:11','',0,'http://blog.calloftheforest.com/?p=131',0,'post','',0),(132,1,'2016-10-14 14:26:31','2016-10-14 14:26:31','','Nothing is black or white','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2016-10-14 14:26:31','2016-10-14 14:26:31','',131,'http://blog.calloftheforest.com/131-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(133,1,'2017-11-14 16:52:32','2017-11-14 16:52:32','<p>I have been consuming a vegan and organic diet for the past two years. I made the decision for ethical reasons due to my concerns with the mistreatment of animals in the meat and dairy industry as well as the strain that animal agriculture and chemicals have on the environment.</p>\n<p>Initially this was a relaxed decision, however as the years have gone¬†by I am finding it increasingly difficult to eat meat, dairy or un-organic food.</p>\n<p>Eating a vegan diet¬†has an interesting learning curve.¬† One has to meet all¬†their nutritional requirements without meat or dairy sources.¬† It\'s not impossible but it does take some careful choices and a clear understanding of the nutrients we need and in what foods they are found.¬† It also requires listening to your body and noticing when things aren\'t quite right.</p>\n<p>I\'ve noticed that I¬†depend on¬†¬†lots of¬†\'exotic\' ingredients that aren\'t sourced locally.¬† Things like hemp seeds, chia seeds and Spirulina.¬† In fact most of my protein sources like chickpeas, kidney beans, quinoa and lentils are not sourced locally.¬† It has me wondering if I am creating a¬†bigger carbon footprint than if I just ate locally sourced ingredients which might include meat and dairy.</p>\n<p>The point is that if¬†it were proven that my carbon footprint¬†was larger than if I ate locally sourced foods I would need to reconsider my choices.¬† Which brings me back to the difficulty I have eating meat, dairy or un-organic food.¬† Have I become identified with being vegan?¬† Does it give me satisfaction to say \'I\'m vegan\'?¬† Do I think I am better than others and judge them because they aren\'t vegan?¬† Being identified with veganism is of little benefit as it means that I¬†have become¬†closed to new¬†information and defensive about my¬†opinions.</p>\n<p>That\'s why I¬†believe that eating consciously is most important.¬† It\'s not about making judgements or identifications, its about doing what is right for the greater good.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"s1\">In every truth the opposite is equally true.¬†</span><span class=\"s2\">That is to say, any truth can only be expressed and put into words when it is one-sided. Everything that can be thought with the mind and said with words is one-sided, it\'s all just the half of it, lacking completeness, roundness, or unity.</span></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"s2\">Siddhartha by Hermann Hesse</span></p>','Nothing is black or white','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-autosave-v1','','','2017-11-14 16:52:32','2017-11-14 16:52:32','',131,'http://blog.calloftheforest.com/131-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(134,1,'2016-10-14 14:29:09','2016-10-14 14:29:09','<p class=\"p1\"><strong>I have been a consuming a vegan diet¬†for the past year. I made the decision for ethical reason due to my concerns with animal mistreatment and the strain that animal based diets places on the environment.</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Initially this was a relaxed decision, however as the year has gone on, I have found myself informing friends and family of my dietary requirements and expecting them to cater for me when i visit.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">During this year it has been a learning experience to understand how to meet my body‚Äôs nutritional requirements without meat sources. I found I needed many exotic ingredients that could not be sourced locally. When faced with the fact that they could be causing a bigger carbon footprint that a locally sourced diet incorporating meat, I was resistant, I had become identified with being a vegan.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">It is certainly not a black and white subject and rather than being vegan we should be eating¬†consciously<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">,¬†</span>otherwise there is danger in identifying with these choices and not being open to new information or different opinions. I will no longer expect people to cater for my personal choice. When I am preparing and choosing food for myself I will go vegan where possible, but when with others I will respect their decisions.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">In this world of polarised opinions this is surely the only way to move forward, to give each other respect, to listen<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">¬† </span>and to accept that we may be wrong.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"s1\">In every truth the opposite is equally true.¬†</span><span class=\"s2\">That is to say, any truth can only be expressed and put into words when it is one-sided. Everything that can be thought with the mind and said with words is one-sided, it\'s all just the half of it, lacking completeness, roundness, or unity.</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"s2\">Siddhartha by Hermann Hesse</span></p>','Nothing is black or white','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v