 Everything that can be thought with the mind and said with words is one-sided, it\'s all just the half of it, lacking completeness, roundness, or unity.</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"s2\">Siddhartha by Hermann Hesse</span></p>','Nothing is black or white','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2017-10-25 17:45:23','2017-10-25 17:45:23','',131,'http://blog.calloftheforest.com/131-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(324,1,'2017-10-27 12:24:50','2017-10-27 12:24:50','<section>\r\n<h2>What is Aya?</h2>\r\nButta is a plant based replacement for dairy butter and can be used for spreading, cooking and baking. Butta looks and tastes like dairy butter. It has a fat content of 75% similar to dairy butter but unlike dairy butter Butta contains 45% saturated, 15% mono-saturated and 18% poly-unsaturated fats making it a healthier choice.\r\n\r\nButta differentiates itself from other margarines by offering an organic margarine spread that contains no mono- and diglycerides of fatty acids (trans-fat) or palm oil. It uses plant milk, not water and its core oils are coconut oil and cocoa butter. Butta is packaged in greaseproof paper with a cardboard sleeve and uses no plastic packaging.\r\n<dl>\r\n 	<dt>Butta ingredients:</dt>\r\n 	<dd><i></i>GMO (genetically modified organics) free</dd>\r\n 	<dd><i></i>Dairy free</dd>\r\n 	<dd><i></i>Lactose free</dd>\r\n 	<dd><i></i>Gluten free</dd>\r\n 	<dd><i></i>Palm oil free</dd>\r\n 	<dd><i></i>No Hexane</dd>\r\n 	<dd><i></i>No trans or hydrogenated fat</dd>\r\n</dl>\r\n</section>&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Butta an alternative for spreading, cook and baking</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<section>\r\n<h2>Why will consumers buy Butta?</h2>\r\n<i></i><em>The move to plant based alternatives is one of the fastest growing lifestyles in the world.</em>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.vegansociety.com/whats-new/news/find-out-how-many-vegans-are-great-britain\">A study by Ipsos MORI in 2016</a> reveals that there are at least 542,000 vegans (a person who does not eat or use animal products) in Britain, three and a half times as many as there was in 2006.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://ucfoodobserver.com/2015/06/04/report-un-urges-global-move-to-meat-and-dairy-free-diet/\">United Nations Environment Programme</a> highlighted the strain of agricultural products on the environment back in 2010. Consumers are becoming increasingly aware that a switch to plant based foods is required to cut gas greenhouse emissions and sustain the ever increasing population.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://thinkprogress.org/the-netherlands-new-dietary-guidelines-take-meat-off-the-menu-a97c40f05d84#.qqjmqqj68\">New dietary guidelines</a> for the Netherlands, the UK and the US take into account the environmental impact when formulating dietary recommendations promoting plant based-foods over agricultural products.\r\n\r\n<i></i><em>Consumers are choosing foods that contain natural ingredients over \'non-fat\' and \'low-fat\' varieties because they are seen as a more wholesome and healthier choice.</em>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.alternet.org/food/how-low-fat-foods-actually-made-america-fat\">How low-fat foods actually made America fat</a>\r\n\r\nAn article <a href=\"https://blendle.com/i/wsj-com/will-margarine-become-toast-at-unilever/bnl-wsj-20160119-SB12115899085733003306504581487633666776002?sharer=eyJ2ZXJzaW9uIjoiMSIsInVpZCI6ImFteW12YXJnYSIsIml0ZW1faWQiOiJibmwtd3NqLTIwMTYwMTE5LVNCMTIxMTU4OTkwODU3MzMwMDMzMDY1MDQ1ODE0ODc2MzM2NjY3NzYwMDIifQ%3D%3D\">in The Wallstreet Journal</a> reports butter\'s resurgence over margarine (2016)\r\n\r\n<i></i><em>Consumers are making product choices based on the overall impact of the product on the environment most importantly, sustainability.</em>\r\n\r\nOne of Butta\'s core values is to source ingredients from ethical and sustainable suppliers.\r\n\r\nThe European Margarine Association highlights the importance of sustainability <a href=\"http://imace.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/IMACE_Newsletter_lay-out-A4_MAI_v4.pdf\">as a key concept for society, business and policy makers</a>.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.baltimoresun.com/business/bs-bz-supermarket-sustainable-food-trend-20170127-story.html\">Giant Food introduces a ratings system </a>that measures the sustainability of food.\r\n\r\n</section>&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Plant based food product sales topped $4.9B in 2016, growing 3.4% since 2015</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.spins.com/plant-based-foods-webinar/\">Spins Plant Based Foods Growth Opportunities in Retail</a>\r\n\r\n<section>\r\n<h2>Why will retailers choose Butta</h2>\r\n<i></i><em>Sales of plant based foods have outperformed all expectations</em>\r\n\r\nSainsbury\'s vegan cheeses <a href=\"http://www.sainsburysmagazine.co.uk/blog/item/10-things-you-need-to-know-about-going-vegan\">outperformed projected sales targets by 300%</a>\r\n\r\nZizzi restaurants <a href=\"https://www.thecaterer.com/articles/495103/zizzi-reports-150-increase-in-vegan-dish-sales\">reported a 150% increase in vegan dish sales.</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.tidefordorganics.com/\">Tide Ford Organics</a> have revamped their range to be completely vegan.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.pret.co.uk/en-gb/little-veggie-pop-up\">Pret\'s Veggie Store</a> is so popular it is here to stay.\r\n\r\nEven <a href=\"http://www.benjerry.com/flavors/non-dairy\">Ben and Jerry\'s</a> has a non-dairy flavours.\r\n\r\n67% of consumers in the US choose plant based milks because they like the taste of it and 65% of consumers choose plant based milks because it\'s healthier than dairy.\r\n\r\n<i></i><em>As margarine sales flatten, Butta offers a plant based alternative that not only looks, tastes and behaves like dairy butter but offers all the benefits of plant based oils.</em>\r\n\r\nRetail butter compound annual growth rate (CAGR) forecast for 2015-2020 is 0.4% compared with margarine\'s -0.6%. Butta bridges the gap between the popularity of plant based foods and the resurgence in butter sales.\r\n\r\n</section>&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Vegans are inspired by health, the environment and animal welfare</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<section>\r\n<h2>Who is the target market for Butta</h2>\r\n<i></i><em>Millenials (born between 1977 and 2000)</em>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.vegansociety.com/whats-new/news/find-out-how-many-vegans-are-great-britain\">A study by Ipsos MORI in 2016</a>reveals that 42% of all vegans in the UK are between the ages of 18 and 34.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.spins.com/plant-based-foods-webinar/\">Spins Plant Based Foods Growth Opportunities in Retail</a> reports that in the US 1 in 10 millenials (born between 1977 and 2000) are vegan and vegetarian.\r\n\r\n<i></i><em>Living in urban and suburban areas</em>\r\n\r\nIn the UK 82% of all vegans live in urban and suburban areas and London contains 22% of all vegans.\r\n\r\n<i></i><em>Inspired to make vegan or vegetarian choices because of animal welfare, the environment or health</em>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/global/2016/sep/11/why-so-many-people-are-converting-to-veganism\">The Guardian</a> recently profiled 4 vegans and their motivation for converting to veganism\r\n\r\n</section><section>\r\n<h2>What makes Butta healthy?</h2>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div><img src=\"http://blog.calloftheforest.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/cocoanut.png\" width=\"138\" height=\"89\" /></div>\r\n<h4>Coconut oil (28%)</h4>\r\nCoconut oil is <em>good for cholesterol</em>, its high Lauric acid content means that its energy is absorbed quickly giving a <em>satisfying</em> feeling of fullness. It also has <em>antimicrobial</em> properties which fight viruses and bacterial infections.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div><img src=\"http://blog.calloftheforest.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/canola.png\" height=\"89\" /></div>\r\n<h4>Canola oil (26%)</h4>\r\nCanola oil has the <em>lowest saturated fat</em> content of all plant oils. Its beneficial high mono-unsaturated fat content protects our heart by maintaining good cholesterol levels and it contains both <em>omega-3</em> and <em>omega-6</em> essential fatty acids.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div><img src=\"http://blog.calloftheforest.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/cocoa.png\" width=\"138\" height=\"89\" /></div>\r\n<h4>Cocoa butter (21%)</h4>\r\nCocoa butter is an excellent source of natural <em>anti-oxidants</em>, omega-3 and omega-6 essential fatty acids as well as nutrients that enhance the mood and <em>immune system</em>.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</section>','About Aya for retailers','','inherit','closed','closed','','146-revision-v1','','','2017-10-27 12:24:50','2017-10-27 12:24:50','',146,'http://blog.calloftheforest.com/146-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(325,1,'2017-10-27 17:25:14','2017-10-27 17:25:14','<p class=\"p1\">I have been consuming a vegan and organic diet for the past two years. I made the decision for ethical reasons due to my concerns with the mistreatment of animals in the meat and dairy industry as well as the strain that animal agriculture and chemicals have on the environment.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Initially this was a relaxed decision, however as the years have gone¬†by I am finding it increasingly difficult to eat meat, dairy or un-organic food.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Eating a vegan diet¬†has an interesting learning curve.¬† One has to meet all¬†their nutritional requirements without meat or dairy sources.¬† It\'s not impossible but it does take some careful choices and a clear understanding of the nutrients we need and in what foods they are found.¬† It also requires listening to your body and noticing when things aren\'t quite right.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">I\'ve noticed that I¬†depend on¬†¬†lots of¬†\'exotic\' ingredients that aren\'t sourced locally.¬† Things like hemp seeds, chia seeds and Spirulina.¬† In fact most of my protein sources like chickpeas, kidney beans, quinoa and lentils are not sourced locally.¬† It has me wondering if I am creating a¬†bigger carbon footprint than if I just ate locally sourced ingredients which might include meat and dairy.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The point is that if¬†it could be proven that my carbon footprint¬†was bigger than if I ate locally sourced foods I would need to reconsider my choices.¬† Which brings me back to the difficulty I have eating meat, dairy or un-organic food.¬† Have I become identified with being vegan?¬† Does it give me satisfaction to say I\'m vegan?¬† Do I think I am better than others and judge them because they aren\'t vegan?¬† Being identified with veganism is of little benefit as it means that I¬†have become¬†closed to new¬†information and defensive about my¬†opinions.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">That\'s why I¬†believe that eating consciously is more important.¬† It\'s not about making judgements or identifications, its about doing what is right for the greater good.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"s1\">In every truth the opposite is equally true.¬†</span><span class=\"s2\">That is to say, any truth can only be expressed and put into words when it is one-sided. Everything that can be thought with the mind and said with words is one-sided, it\'s all just the half of it, lacking completeness, roundness, or unity.</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"s2\">Siddhartha by Hermann Hesse</span></p>','Nothing is black or lite','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2017-10-27 17:25:14','2017-10-27 17:25:14','',131,'http://blog.calloftheforest.com/131-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(326,1,'2017-10-27 17:27:20','2017-10-27 17:27:20','<p class=\"p1\">I have been consuming a vegan and organic diet for the past two years. I made the decision for ethical reasons due to my concerns with the mistreatment of animals in the meat and dairy industry as well as the strain that animal agriculture and chemicals have on the environment.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Initially this was a relaxed decision, however as the years have gone¬†by I am finding it increasingly difficult to eat meat, dairy or un-organic food.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Eating a vegan diet¬†has an interesting learning curve.¬† One has to meet all¬†their nutritional requirements without meat or dairy sources.¬† It\'s not impossible but it does take some careful choices and a clear understanding of the nutrients we need and in what foods they are found.¬† It also requires listening to your body and noticing when things aren\'t quite right.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">I\'ve noticed that I¬†depend on¬†¬†lots of¬†\'exotic\' ingredients that aren\'t sourced locally.¬† Things like hemp seeds, chia seeds and Spirulina.¬† In fact most of my protein sources like chickpeas, kidney beans, quinoa and lentils are not sourced locally.¬† It has me wondering if I am creating a¬†bigger carbon footprint than if I just ate locally sourced ingredients which might include meat and dairy.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The point is that if¬†it could be proven that my carbon footprint¬†was bigger than if I ate locally sourced foods I would need to reconsider my choices.¬† Which brings me back to the difficulty I have eating meat, dairy or un-organic food.¬† Have I become identified with being vegan?¬† Does it give me satisfaction to say I\'m vegan?¬† Do I think I am better than others and judge them because they aren\'t vegan?¬† Being identified with veganism is of little benefit as it means that I¬†have become¬†closed to new¬†information and defensive about my¬†opinions.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">That\'s why I¬†believe that eating consciously is more important.¬† It\'s not about making judgements or identifications, its about doing what is right for the greater good.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"s1\">In every truth the opposite is equally true.¬†</span><span class=\"s2\">That is to say, any truth can only be expressed and put into words when it is one-sided. Everything that can be thought with the mind and said with words is one-sided, it\'s all just the half of it, lacking completeness, roundness, or unity.</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"s2\">Siddhartha by Hermann Hesse</span></p>','Nothing is black or white','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2017-10-27 17:27:20','2017-10-27 17:27:20','',131,'http://blog.calloftheforest.com/131-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(327,1,'2017-10-30 15:58:32','2017-10-30 15:58:32','Welcome to Aya. We believe that living plant-strong is similar to a future dominated by clean, renewable energy. We invite you to #jointheAYAlution and help us in our mission to reduce animal agriculture.\r\n\r\nWe\'re more than just plant-based we are creating a conscious business¬†that cares about its employees, the environment, our community and our shareholders. We prioritise sustainability and ethics and our purpose is to reduce animal agriculture by providing delicious plant based products.\r\n\r\nAya is an African goddess of forests, animals and herbal healing. Inspired by her, our organic plantbutter is kinder to the animals, the earth and ourselves (Aya Original contains 10% less fat than cow\'s butter and 9% less saturated fat).','About Aya','','inherit','closed','closed','','297-revision-v1','','','2017-10-30 15:58:32','2017-10-30 15:58:32','',297,'http://blog.calloftheforest.com/297-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(328,1,'2017-10-30 15:59:58','2017-10-30 15:59:58','<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Times New Roman\', serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">Aya Original was created in my kitchen because, having taken up a vegan life-style, I didn\'t want to miss out on the enjoyment of butter. I created Aya Original as the closest plant alternative to cow\'s butter. Aya Original is made with coconut oil, cacao butter and safflower oil. The coconut oil and cacao butter have been steamed to remove their flavours. Cacao butter is what makes Aya so melty, it also helps it stay hard at room temperature. The safflower oil is cold pressed which is a great way of maintaining its nutritional benefits. Just like cow\'s butter Aya Original is high in fat. Aya Original has 10% lower overall fat than cow\'s butter and 9% less saturated fat. Enjoy Aya Original responsibly!</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Times New Roman\', serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">Aya Original is great for toast and can be used for spreading, cooking and baking. Unlike a lot of other spreads on the market Aya contains no palm oil. It is organic, contains no GMO ingredients, </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Times New Roman\', serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">and is made with 6 simple ingredients. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"western\">Dietary and lifestyle</h4>\r\n<p class=\"western\">ONLY ORGANIC INGREDIENTS</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">No PALM OIL</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">No GMO INGREDIENTS</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">No DAIRY OR LACTOSE</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Suitable for VEGANS and VEGETARIANS</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"western\">Ingredients</h4>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Organic steamed coconut oil (29%), organic steamed cocoa butter (22%), organic cold-pressed safflower oil (20%), spring water, Himalayan pink salt (1.4%), organic sunflower lecithin (vegetable fat 71%)</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"western\">Typical nutritional values per 100g</h4>\r\n<table border=\"1\" width=\"100%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\"><colgroup><col width=\"64*\" /> <col width=\"64*\" /> <col width=\"64*\" /> <col width=\"64*\" /> </colgroup>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr valign=\"TOP\">\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">Typical values</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">Per 100g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">Per 10g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">RI% based on 10g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr valign=\"TOP\">\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">Energy (kJ / kCal)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">2636 / 636</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">263 / 63</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">3%</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr valign=\"TOP\">\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">Total fat</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Saturated</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">71g</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">42g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">7.1g</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">4.2g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">10%</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">21%</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr valign=\"TOP\">\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">Carbohydrates</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">0g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">0g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">0</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr valign=\"TOP\">\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">Sugar</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">0g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">0g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">0</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr valign=\"TOP\">\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">Fibre</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">0g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">0g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">0</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr valign=\"TOP\">\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">Protein</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">0g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">0g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">0</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr valign=\"TOP\">\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">Salt</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">1.34g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">0.134g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"25%\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">2.24%</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h4 class=\"western\">How is Aya Original made?</h4>\r\n<p class=\"western\">The oils are melted to liquid form and blended with spring water, oil and a small amount of sunflower lecithin and then put in the fridge to set.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"western\">Where are Aya Original\'s ingredients from?</h4>\r\n<p class=\"western\">We source our organic steamed cocoa butter from RealFoodSource who import the cacao from Dominican Republic. Our organic steamed coconut oil is purchased from Biona whose coconut oils originate from SriLanka and the Philippines. Our organic cold-pressed safflower oil is purchased from Kerfoot Group and originates from TO DO:</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"western\">What are the health risks associated with Aya Original?</h4>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Just like cow\'s butter Aya Original contains a high overall fat content which is composed mostly of saturated fats. Whilst Aya Original contains 10% less overall fat and 9% less saturated fat then cow\'s butter it should be consumed responsibly. Eating high levels of saturated fat can raise your cholesterol and increase your risk of heart disease.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Aya Original contains 0.7% sunflower lecithin which makes it creamy and spreadable. Sunflower lecithin contains &lt;1g of trans-fat per 100g.</p>','AYA','','inherit','closed','closed','','287-revision-v1','','','2017-10-30 15:59:58','2017-10-30 15:59:58','',287,'http://blog.calloftheforest.com/287-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(329,1,'2017-10-30 17:10:46','2017-10-30 17:10:46','<p>We value your feedback! We can only grow and develop with you in mind.  Please share your opinions, inspiration, photos, questions, recipes, whatever you have in mind, we can\'t wait to hear fro