 to endure a week of big panties (for safety) and sitting in blood soaked pads for hours (so gross)!  Plus there\'s no smells!  Considering all the benefits of a menstrual cup including the one closest to my heart, reducing environmental waste, why aren\'t pad and tampon companies switching to menstrual cups and why aren\'t these sold in the grocery stores?\r\n\r\nSo how was the iCare menstrual cup?  The experience of inserting a silicon cup up your v-jay-jay certainly does take some getting used too.  Like anyone who has inserted anything up their vagina there is a constant awareness that this must also come out.  The iCare cup has a short pulling bit which sits just inside your vagina so it\'s discreet and doesn\'t get in the way.  This does make it bit scary in the beginning, the thought that the cup may somehow get too high and I wouldn\'t be able to find the tag to pull it out.  But fear not, this never  happened not even after running, yoga and climbing.  Fortunately for me I have a manicured vagina but a bushy vagina might inevitably mean accidentally tugging on a few hairs which could be quite painful.\r\n\r\nIn the beginning I struggled with the concept of making sure the cup opened inside my vagina, so that it was a tight fit and didn\'t leak. Basically you fold the cup to insert it and once it is inside your cervix it opens up (that sounds way more complicated then it is so please don\'t let it put you off).  Once I followed the instructions carefully and developed a little more confidence this wasn\'t a struggle at all and never had a leak.\r\n\r\nOther than that I did have some weird thoughts about this cup of blood sloshing around inside me especially when I did inversion asanas (shoulder stands) in yoga.  It suddenly made sense why inversion asanas may not be recommend when menstruating.  I tend to remove and empty the cup every 3 to 4 hours but you can leave it in for up to 12 hours.  In fact menstrual cups have a lower risk of TSS http://www.webmd.com/women/guide/menstrual-cup#1 which makes it quite safe.  \r\n\r\nWashing out of the cup isn\'t convenient when you\'re in public places where the sink is outside of the toilet cubicle.  I think the best thing to do is bring a bottle of water with you and wash it into the toilet.\r\n\r\nWith reference to the iCare cup I am wondering if the silicon is a little hard next month I am going to order the Mooncup which emphasises a softer silicon.  I\'ll let you know how I get on. \r\n\r\nI ordered a Mooncup for a whopping ¬£20 (with delivery).  That\'s 5x more expensive then the iCare cup and sadly I preferred the iCare version.  There are two reasons.  One  is that the  Mooncup has a very thick rim of silicon around its top which I presume is to create a snugger fit but I found that made it way more difficult to insert.  Also the Mooncup cup is smaller so the tag sits a little higher which wasn\'t so great, well quite scary in fact.  \r\n\r\nSecond month in and I love menstrual cups.  What a pleasure!  They\'re so convenient, if you think you\'re coming on they fit discreetly in your bag and you only ever need one.  This time around I left the cup in way longer and was quite comfortable with it.  One thing I would recommend though is wearing black panties because you can get a smear or two (though never any leakage!) and you don\'t want to ruin your favourite pair of lingerie. \r\n\r\nI hope you\'ll try a menstrual cup soon.  It\'ll be great for the planet and I am sure you will love their benefits too.\r\n\r\n','Are menstrual cups the future?','','inherit','closed','closed','','304-revision-v1','','','2017-11-15 14:26:38','2017-11-15 14:26:38','',304,'http://blog.calloftheforest.com/304-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(388,1,'2017-11-15 20:34:14','2017-11-15 20:34:14','<p>Aya has been created out of a need to live and work authentically with a vision of earning a fair livelihood whilst contributing positively to society.  We believe that our business should hold your 